I now have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Here is the complete implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Canvas Posts in Homepage Feed

### Overview

The card rendering for canvas posts already exists in `PostCards.jsx` (lines 516-572) with `CanvasPreview`, action buttons, and the `is-canvas-card` class. The CSS for canvas card accents also exists in `canvaspreview.css`. The work is primarily: (1) remove the filter, (2) clean up now-unnecessary search-only-canvas logic, and (3) add a badge element with CSS.

---

### Step 1: Remove the Canvas Filter from Feed Data (PostCards.jsx)

**File:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\postCards\PostCards.jsx`

**Line 378-379** -- Change from:
```javascript
const feedJournals = (data?.pages?.flatMap((page) => page.data || []) || [])
    .filter((journal) => journal?.post_type !== 'canvas');
```
To:
```javascript
const feedJournals = (data?.pages?.flatMap((page) => page.data || []) || []);
```

**Line 380-382** -- Also remove the canvas filter from search results. Change from:
```javascript
const rawSearchedJournals = searchData?.data || [];
const searchedJournals = rawSearchedJournals
    .filter((journal) => journal?.post_type !== 'canvas');
```
To:
```javascript
const searchedJournals = searchData?.data || [];
```

**Lines 385-388** -- Remove the `hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches` variable entirely since canvas posts now appear inline:
```javascript
// DELETE these lines:
const hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches = isSearchMode
    && rawSearchedJournals.length > 0
    && searchedJournals.length === 0
    && rawSearchedJournals.every((journal) => journal?.post_type === 'canvas');
```

**Line 384** -- Simplify (no longer need `rawSearchedJournals`):
```javascript
const journals = isSearchMode ? searchedJournals : feedJournals;
```
This line stays the same -- it already works.

---

### Step 2: Remove the "Canvas matches found in Gallery" Hint (PostCards.jsx)

Since canvas posts now appear in search results directly, remove the gallery redirect hint.

**Lines 432-440** -- Delete the entire `hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches` conditional block:
```jsx
// DELETE this block:
{hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches && !isSearchFetching && (
    <button
        type="button"
        className="search-gallery-hint"
        onClick={() => navigate('/home/gallery')}
    >
        Canvas matches found in Gallery
    </button>
)}
```

**Line 494** -- Simplify the empty state class (remove the canvas-only variant):
```jsx
// Change from:
<div className={`search-empty-state ${hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches ? 'is-canvas-only' : ''}`}>
// To:
<div className="search-empty-state">
```

**Lines 497-507** -- Remove the `hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches` branch from the empty state ternary. Change from:
```jsx
{journals.length === 0 && !isLoading && (
    <div className="search-empty-state">
        {!isSearchMode ? (
            'No post available...'
        ) : hasOnlyCanvasSearchMatches ? (
            <>
                All matches are canvas posts.{' '}
                <button type="button" className="search-empty-link"
                    onClick={() => navigate('/home/gallery')}>
                    View canvas matches in Gallery
                </button>
            </>
        ) : isSearchMode ? (
            'No matching posts found.'
        ) : (
            'No post available...'
        )}
    </div>
)}
```
To:
```jsx
{journals.length === 0 && !isLoading && (
    <div className="search-empty-state">
        {isSearchMode ? 'No matching posts found.' : 'No post available...'}
    </div>
)}
```

---

### Step 3: Add Canvas Badge Markup (PostCards.jsx)

Inside the card's `card-content` div, add an inline badge right before the title. This positions it as a type indicator that reads naturally with the title.

**Around line 548** -- Inside `.feed-title-content`, add a badge before the `<h2>`. Change from:
```jsx
<div className="feed-title-content">
    <h2 className="feed-title">{journal.title.length > 55 ? `${journal.title.substring(0, 55)}...` : journal.title}</h2>
</div>
```
To:
```jsx
<div className="feed-title-content">
    {isCanvasPost && (
        <span className="canvas-type-badge">
            <svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" strokeWidth="2.2" strokeLinecap="round" strokeLinejoin="round">
                <path d="M12 19l7-7 3 3-7 7-3-3z"/>
                <path d="M18 13l-1.5-7.5L2 2l3.5 14.5L13 18l5-5z"/>
                <path d="M2 2l7.586 7.586"/>
                <circle cx="11" cy="11" r="2"/>
            </svg>
            Canvas
        </span>
    )}
    <h2 className="feed-title">{journal.title.length > 55 ? `${journal.title.substring(0, 55)}...` : journal.title}</h2>
</div>
```

The SVG is a pen-nib/brush icon that signals "creative tool". It is inline SVG to avoid an extra import and matches the pattern used elsewhere in the codebase (e.g., the search icon in the same file).

